     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td valign="top" background="images/background_image2.png" align="left">
      <table width="1024" border="0" align="center" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
       <tbody>
        <tr>
         <th width="410" valign="bottom" align="center" scope="col">
          <blockquote>
           <p>
            <img width="326" height="251" align="middle" alt="Scaublin Lathe - BW Clocks - Clock Repair and Servicing" src="images/ber1.jpg" />
            <br />
           </p>
           <p>
            <em>
             My Schaublin lathe
            </em>
           </p>
          </blockquote>
         </th>
         <th width="614" valign="top" align="left" scope="col">
          <blockquote>
           <p>
            <br />
            In 1967 I was apprenticed to F J Lees in Nottingham, who at that time were principally trade watch and clock repairers. The two partners were both Fellows of the British Horological Institute, and encouraged me to gain a place at Hackney Technical College where I was able to study practical and theoretical horology in London. On passing all grades of the BHI examinations first class, I returned to Lees from this 2 year course in 1969, and completed my apprenticeship in 1972, when I was awarded Fellowship of the BHI.
           </p>
           <p>
            Later in1972 I joined the firm of Meyrick Neilson Ltd, in Tetbury, and spent the next 6 years working on a mouthwatering collection of the nicest English and French antique clocks. Most of the time we were preparing these clocks for sale, and the experience I gained at that time would be very difficult to get today.
           </p>
          </blockquote>
          <blockquote>
           <p>
            When this firm closed in 1978 I returned to Nottingham to work as a self employed trade clockmaker, and eventually rejoined Lees as a partner. In 1983 I was recruited by the Marconi company to introduce and apply horological techniques to the millimetre wave radar industry.
           </p>
          </blockquote>
         </th>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>
     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td valign="top" background="images/background_image2.png" align="left">
      <blockquote>
       <p>
        <strong>
         The miniaturisation of electronic components had rapidly overtaken the ability of the industry to make all the associated mechanical components that were needed to build small radar systems, and some far sighted individual had the idea to employ an horologist. I have worked in this fascinating field until the present day, but have now decided to return to clock making as my main occupation, covering Nottinghamshire, Lincolnshire and Leicestershire.
        </strong>
       </p>
      </blockquote>
     </td>
